    <Entry>
      <ID>192</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Captain!" shouts Vostiel. He turns you over. "Moon of Fortune, he's alive! You got it, captain. The big bastard is face down and smoking! You got it!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>193</ID>
      <DefaultText>You can't reply. The world is dilating down to a pinhole, but you feel Vostiel take the beamer from your hands and squeeze your arm. "We'll take it from here, captain. Only clean up to do now. Hang on. You won the day. The glory is yours. Priest, see to him, I beg you!"

The last thing you hear, as the silver rain beats down on your upturned face and consciousness begins to leave you, is the voice of the priest. "You'd be alive if you'd let me use my weapon. Guess you'd rather be a dead hero, damned fool." 

{SOUND: All sounds fade except the rain.}
{ART: Illustration - Dead Captain}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>194</ID>
      <DefaultText>"No. There's no point in killing ourselves for this.  Fall back and return to the company."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>195</ID>
      <DefaultText>Vostiel and Alvoosh, the other surviving member of the squad, are sullen at this decision, but they obey the order nonetheless, and, much to the Aeon Priest's relief, within a half hour, you are back with Landi and the main company and back on the road, marching for headquarters once again. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>196</ID>
      <DefaultText>As one, you and Vostiel lob your detonators. Vostiel's bounces right into the enclosure, and you hear the enemy shriek in fear as they try to escape it. With its inhuman reaction time, however, the construct catches yours in its remaining pincer, but isn't fast enough to prevent it from detonating. 

Unfortunately, it *is* fast enough to get off one more shot before the cypher's implosion collapses it and everything around it into a single point. A searing beam stabs through you from clavicle to pelvis, cooking everything in between. 

"Captain!" shouts Vostiel. He turns you over. "Moon of Fortune, you're alive! You got it, captain! The big bastard is dead! And the squad too!"

{SOUND: Two sonic booms.}
{ART: Illustration - Blowing Up the Construct}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>197</ID>
      <DefaultText>Finally, you're within throwing range, and as the hulking mantis comes once more around the monolith, you key your aether-com to signal the squad. At the signal, they start firing into the air from behind the ridge, drawing the eyes of both the construct and the soldiers in the enplacement. Now's your time!</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>198</ID>
      <DefaultText>As one, you and Vostiel lob your detonators - yours at the construct, his at the soldiers. Your throws are perfect. Vostiel's bounces right into the emplacement, and you hear the soldiers' shrieks of fear as they try to escape it. With its inhuman reaction time, the construct catches yours in its remaining pincer, but it's too late to prevent it from detonating. 

Unfortunately, its reaction time *is* fast enough for it to get off one more shot before the cypher's implosion collapses it and everything within a ten meter radius of it into a single point, and a searing beam of light stabs straight through your body top to bottom, clavicle to pelvis, and cooking everything in between. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>199</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Captain!" shouts Vostiel. He turns you over. "Moon of Fortune, you're alive! You got it, captain! The big bastard is gone for good! And the squad too!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>200</ID>
      <DefaultText>You can't reply. The world is dilating down to a pinhole, but you feel Vostiel squeeze your arm. "We'll take it from here, captain. Only the patrols to take care of now. Hang on. You won the day. The glory is yours. Priest, see to him, I beg you!"

The last thing you hear, as the silver rain beats down on your upturned face and consciousness begins to leave you, is the voice of the priest, coming closer."You'd be alive if you'd let me use my weapon. Guess you'd rather be a dead hero, damned fool."  

{SOUND: All sounds fade except the rain.}
{ART: Illustration - Dead Captain}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>201</ID>
      <DefaultText>Your squad spreads out and takes cover in the rubble along the circuit of the enemy patrols, then takes them out with silent sliver spitters that paralyze them with poison before they can sound the alarm.

Unfortunately, one of your soldiers misfires during the attack on the last pair and the final scout manages a squawk of surprise before she dies.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>202</ID>
      <DefaultText>You hear shouts of alarm from the enclosure near the monolith, and the ground shakes from the thudding steps of the war-mantis. You order the others to take cover and they hit the mud just as the construct tops the low ridge, haloed by the light behind it and dripping with rain. 

It pauses on the ridge top, examining the dead patrols, then starts limping forward, its head swiveling back and forth, looking for movement. It's only a matter of time before it finds you all. Staying still is not an option. You must make a move.

{SOUND: Robot Movement.}
{ART: Illustration - The Construct Scanning}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>203</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Fire on its legs! It's our only chance!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>204</ID>
      <DefaultText>You rise up with the others and fire on the mantis's forelegs, centering your fire where its armor is most damaged, and causing it to fall flat on its face.

Unfortunately, in the second that it takes it to fall, it spits three beams in three different directions and half your squad is dead - including Vostiel - all burning like candles. And a second later it's pushing itself up again on its one remaining arm.

You fire again, trying to hit its single deadly eye, but it is faster - much faster - and a searing beam of light stabs through you from clavicle to pelvis, cooking everything in between. {SOUND: Robot's powerful beam weapon .}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>205</ID>
      <DefaultText>You fire again, trying to hit its single deadly eye, but it is faster - much faster - and a searing beam of light stabs straight through your body top to bottom, clavicle to pelvis, and cooking everything in between. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>206</ID>
      <DefaultText>The last things you hear, as the black rain beats down on the side of your face and consciousness begins to leave you, are the terrified weeping of the Aeon Priest in his hiding place, and the angry screams of your two last squad members as they charge toward the construct and their certain doom to avenge your brave and glorious death.


{SOUND: All sounds fade except the rain.}
{ART: Illustration - Dead Captain}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>207</ID>
      <DefaultText>Lob a singularity detonator at it.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>208</ID>
      <DefaultText>You pull the detonator from your bandolier and prime it, then hurl it at the mantis. Unfortunately, the second after the cypher leaves your hand, the mantis shoots you, sending a searing beam of light straight through your body, and cooking your insides black. In the next second, it has batted the cypher aside, right where your troopers are lying in cover. 

{SOUND: Sonic boom.}
{ART: Illustration - Blowing up the Construct}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>209</ID>
      <DefaultText>The second to last thing you hear, as the black rain beats down on the side of your face, and consciousness begins to leave you, is the thunderclap of the singularity detonator's implosion swallowing half your squad, and the sizzling whine of the construct's beamer cutting down the rest as they try to flee.

The very last thing you hear is the hopeless weeping of the Aeon Priest in his hiding place. "You fool," he says. "I told you. I told you."

{SOUND: All sounds fade except the rain.}
{ART: Illustration - Dead Captain}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>210</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Run! It's our only chance!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>211</ID>
      <DefaultText>You rise up with the others and flee into the night. Unfortunately, in three seconds it has shot all six of you, and you splash down into the mud, screaming as your insides cook within you. 

{SOUND: Robot's powerful beam weapon.}
{ART: Illustration - Run Away}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>212</ID>
      <DefaultText>The last thing you see, as the black rain beats down on the side of your face, and consciousness begins to leave you, is the priest lying beside you, pointing at you and mouthing, with his dying breath, one word. 

"Fool."

{SOUND: All sounds fade except the rain.}
{ART: Illustration - Dead Captain}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>213</ID>
      <DefaultText>"A needless waste of lives," says the priest as your squad slips between the patrols.

They spread out behind a low ridge so the construct will have a harder time killing them all at once, then trap the approaches to their positions in preparation for any counterattack.

When they're ready, you give the signal, and the squad pours fire at the construct's damaged front legs, hoping to collapse it.

It works! The construct's front legs buckle and it topples. Unfortunately, in the second that it takes it to fall on its face, it spits three beams in three different directions and half your squad is dead, burning like candles. {SOUND: Robot's powerful beam weapon}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>214</ID>
      <DefaultText>"A needless waste of lives," says the the priest as you and Vostiel pull singularity detonators from your bandoliers and start forward.

You slip through the patrols to the crest of the ridge, then wait until the construct has gone behind the monolith and creep over. And that is how you proceed for the next half hour. Moving only when the monolith blocks the construct's vision, then holding as it limps by on another pass.

Finally, you're within throwing range, and as it comes into view once more, you key your aether-com to signal the squad. At the click, they start firing from behind the ridge, drawing the eyes of the construct and the troopers in the enclosure. Now's your chance!

{SOUND: Energy weapon fire.}
{ART: Illustration - Sniping the Construct}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>215</ID>
      <DefaultText>The priest shakes his head as your squad spreads out and takes cover in the rubble along the path of the enemy patrols. 

"A needless waste of lives," he says. "Disgusting." 

As the patrols pass your troopers take them out with silent sliver spitters tipped with a chemical that paralyses them before they can sound the alarm.

All except the last one. A misfire allows the final scout a squawk of surprise before he dies.

{SOUND: Energy weapon fire.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>216</ID>
      <DefaultText>The men gratefully drop their packs and huddle together to share some kind of sour, dried meat over the warmth of a heating cypher. Minutes later, a harsh whine penetrates the hiss of the rain. 

"It's Vostiel," says your lieutenant, looking around. "Back from his sweep."

Vostiel skims in on a small pod hovering in the air. He stops in front of you, pulls off his goggles and salutes.

"Luck's holding, captain," he says. "Early leave and now this: I intercepted a courier with an interesting dispatch on him. Seems the unit that holds Barhad's Monolith has been reduced to ten men by an attack from a rogue construct. They downed the bastard, but it near to wiped them."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>217</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Let's hold until Vostiel returns and we hear his info. Company! Hold and fall out!" </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>218</ID>
      <DefaultText>Only a short while later, just as evening is turning the rain from silver to slate, and the endless vista of trenches and dead constructs on either side of you begins to vanish beyond your lights, your aether-com squawks a warning from your point man, then cuts off again just as abruptly. 

"Trouble," says Vostiel. "I'll go ahead."

"You'll wait for orders, curse you," says Landi. "Captain, what should we do?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>219</ID>
      <DefaultText>Your men cheer and raise the Aeon Priest on their shoulders. He'll probably be the only one rewarded for this, but it's still a victory.

{SOUND: All sounds fade except the rain.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>220</ID>
      <DefaultText>"We're not getting paid enough to die for this priest's hide. Get him ready."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>221</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Fine. Either it ends us or it ends them. Sometimes you have to take the risk. Vostiel and Landi, help the priest set it up."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>222</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Sorry, priest. If there is glory to be won today, it'll be ours. Vostiel, Landi, order your troops."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>223</ID>
      <DefaultText>Only a short while later, just as evening is turning the rain from silver to slate, and the endless vista of trenches and dead constructs on either side of you begins to vanish beyond your lights, your aether-com squawks a warning from your point man, then cuts off abruptly. 

"Trouble," says Vostiel. "I'll go ahead."

"You'll wait for orders, curse you," says Landi. "Captain, what should we do?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
